## Reflection — Day 7 Session 1

- Strings are indexed starting at 0
- Negative indexes count from the end — [-1] is last character
- Slicing [start:end] extracts a portion of a string
- .strip() removes whitespace from both ends
- .lower() .upper() .title() standardize capitalisation
- .replace() swaps one substring for another
- .split() breaks a string into a list
- .join() connects a list back into a string
- 'in' checks if a substring exists
- .find() returns the position of a substring
- String cleaning is one of the most used skills in real data work

## Reflection — Day 7 Session 2

- .strip().title() is the standard cleaning combination
- set() after standardizing removes all duplicates
- sorted() puts a set or list in alphabetical order
- .split("|") parses structured data rows
- float() converts a string number to a float for calculations
- Multi-line strings use triple quotes
- .lower().count() does case-insensitive keyword searching
- String parsing is exactly what happens when pandas reads a CSV
